{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"[G3 child-coverage — container review of parent 1f19-adf2-ffb2-4b09 paired with THIS child (S2b b73c: Snapshot cache janitor — reclamation under disk pressure)]\n\nVERDICT: EMPTY G3 findings list. The union of the WHOLE eight-story roster covers every parent acceptance/success criterion; no uncovered parent criterion is attributable to this pairing.\n\n4-bucket coverage map (parent AC -> covering child/children; THIS child's role):\n- Parent AC1 (no attested gate reads working tree; all read a faithful snapshot at the pinned SHA) — FULLY covered by S1 (6d56 materialize) + S3 (fa49 gate re-rooting). STRUCTURAL w.r.t. this child (Scope: \"Out: ... materialization (S1)\"). Not an absence.\n- Parent AC2 (signed verdict binds verified_at_sha via manifest channel; reproducible; no payload bump) — FULLY covered by S4 (30b3). This child claims no signing. STRUCTURAL. Not an absence.\n- Parent AC3 (local mode reads in-place AND cannot sign; documented back-out) — covered by S3 + S4 + S6. Local bypasses the cache; janitor never touches it. STRUCTURAL. Not an absence.\n- Parent AC4 (concurrent gates run without git-lock contention or cross-op corruption; cache + JANITOR reclaim disk under a defined free-space watermark WITHOUT disrupting in-flight reads) — FULLY covered, SPLIT cleanly, with THIS child as SOLE OWNER of the janitor/reclamation clause: its AC1 (reclaim under free-space watermark, LRU by touch-on-read mtime NOT atime, skip grace window, off hot path), AC2 (max-age cold-trim), AC3 (startup sweep), AC4 (byte-total consistent under concurrent populate-vs-evict — no TOCTOU), AC5 (trash-straggler re-drain), AC6 (rename-to-trash THEN rmtree; no in-place delete of a live entry = \"without disrupting in-flight reads\", riding S2 70c7 delete-on-last-close), AC7 (exclusive gc/lock — no concurrent GC pass), AC8 (self-heal). The single-flight + reader-safety + no-git-lock-contention halves are owned by S2 (70c7) + S1. No double-implementation; no gap.\n- Parent AC5 (private-repo fetch failure surfaces actionable credential error) — FULLY covered by S1 + S6. STRUCTURAL w.r.t. this child. Not an absence.\n- Parent AC6 (portable: no external tar; no hardcoded /tmp; flock+mkdir fallback) — FULLY covered by S1 + S6. This child's exclusive flock on gc/lock RIDES the S1 portability seam without re-owning the tar/tmp/fallback sub-clauses. STRUCTURAL. Not an absence.\n- Parent AC7 (operational tunables: free-space watermark, default ref, grace/age windows configurable with documented defaults (S2/S3)) — FULLY covered, SPLIT: THIS child OWNS the watermark + grace + max-age + reverify tunables (its AC9: \"Watermark, grace window, max-age, and reverify period are configurable with documented defaults\"); default ref owned by S3/S5; docs by S6. Carried; not an absence.\n- Parent AC8 (ADR captures architecture + rejected alternatives: PID-lease, payload-schema SHA binding) — FULLY covered, SPLIT: THIS child OWNS the cache/janitor-architecture + rejected-PID+heartbeat-lease ADR (its AC10), matching the parent's \"authored in S2/S4\" assignment; the payload-schema SHA-binding rejected alternative is owned by S4 (30b3) and ADR 0002 by S4b (e308). Each rejected-alternative clause has a named owner. Not an absence.\n- Parent final AC (all EIGHT children closed; make lint + full suite green) — STRUCTURAL/meta epic-completion criterion; covered by the existence of all eight children (this is S2b of 8) + each child's green-bar obligation. Not an absence at this child.\n\nSuccess-criteria narrative: \"SAFELY UNDER CONCURRENT DISTRIBUTED USE\" — specifically reclaiming disk under pressure WITHOUT corrupting concurrent readers (the \"hard part\"/riskiest piece) — is precisely THIS child's core deliverable (AC1-AC8/AC10), atop S2's immutable-SHA content-addressed cache + delete-on-last-close reader safety. The signed/reproducible and unsigned-local clauses are carried by S4/S3. No uncovered obligation introduced by this child.\n\nNamed-consumer / delegation cross-checks (covered-by-named-consumer, not absences): this child delegates the cache read/populate path to S2 (70c7, \"Built ON TOP of the cache story\"; \"Out: the cache read/populate path\") and materialization to S1 (6d56, \"Out: ... materialization (S1)\"). It CONSUMES S2's touch-on-read mtime (LRU signal), S2's incrementally-maintained byte total (the value it reconciles), and S2's delete-on-last-close reader safety (what makes rename-to-trash eviction non-disruptive). Each delegated obligation is claimed by a named sibling present in the roster.\n\nNote (NOT a G3 finding): sibling cache ticket S2 (70c7) still carries the stale title \"+ background janitor\"; the janitor/reclamation/ADR work has been correctly split out to THIS child (S2b). A label/consistency (G4) note on S2, not a G3 union-coverage gap — the reclamation work IS owned by a named child (this one), so the union covers it.\n\nConclusion: this child cleanly OWNS the janitor/reclamation slice — sole owner of parent AC4's \"cache + janitor reclaim disk under a defined free-space watermark without disrupting in-flight reads\" clause, owner of parent AC7's watermark/grace/age tunables, and co-owner (with S4 for the payload-schema rejected alternative) of parent AC8's ADR. Every parent acceptance/success criterion has a named owner in the eight-story roster; none is left uncovered. NO G3 finding for this pairing."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782532174460569001,"uuid":"53c01281-8763-41e2-88cb-6ad9e80a0e53"}